results.satirical_column:
In a stunning display of military genius, the British Army has decided to bolster its ranks by recruiting asthmatics and acne sufferers. Because nothing strikes fear into the heart of the enemy quite like the sight of a soldier fumbling for their inhaler mid-charge or a squadron so spotted they're essentially camouflaged against a strawberry field.

Defence Secretary John Healey, in a move that can only be described as 'scraping the barrel with such vigour he's struck oil', announced plans to end "outdated and unnecessary entry requirements". Next on the chopping block: the ability to walk in a straight line and basic bladder control.

But wait, there's more! In a twist that would make George Orwell slow-clap from beyond the grave, Healey's also eyeing up the crème de la crème of British youth - console warriors. Yes, folks, hours of Call of Duty will now count as military experience. I can already picture the recruitment posters: "Your country needs YOU... to pause that game and pick up a real gun, you pasty-faced basement dweller."

One can only imagine the new training regimens. Will we see obstacle courses featuring strategically placed Ventolin stations? Perhaps camouflage cream that doubles as acne medication? And let's not forget the crucial skill of maintaining steady aim while scratching that pesky zit on your trigger finger.

The possibilities are endless. Maybe we'll pioneer new biological warfare techniques - weaponized acne, anyone? Or perhaps we'll see the first asthma attack used as a battle cry, striking confusion and mild concern into enemy ranks.

But fear not, dear citizens. While our armed forces may soon resemble the reject pile of a Calvin Klein casting call, at least we'll have an army of gamers ready to defend us in the digital realm. Who needs actual combat experience when you've got carpal tunnel syndrome and a kill/death ratio to die for?

In related news, I hear the Royal Navy is considering recruiting people with chronic seasickness. After all, nothing says "Rule, Britannia!" quite like a destroyer's deck awash with vomit.

So sleep soundly, Britain. Your country is in the... well, let's say 'hands' of a military that's boldly redefining what it means to be fighting fit. God save the Queen, and pass the acne cream.

results.satirical_column:
In a move that can only be described as a desperate attempt to bolster Britain's dwindling military ranks, Defence Secretary John Healey has declared open season on asthmatics and acne sufferers. Yes, you heard that right, folks. The once-proud British Army, known for its stiff upper lip and even stiffer uniform collars, is now actively recruiting those who can't catch their breath and those whose faces resemble a topographical map of the Highlands.

One can only imagine the scenes at basic training. Drill sergeants barking orders through nebulizers, while recruits march in formation, leaving a trail of salicylic acid in their wake. "Left, *wheeze* right, *wheeze* left!" It's like a Monty Python sketch come to life, only with less dead parrots and more inhaler-wielding soldiers.

But wait, there's more! In a twist that would make both Sun Tzu and Shigeru Miyamoto scratch their heads, Healey is also on a mission to recruit the nation's top gamers. That's right, the next line of defense against cyber warfare will be manned by energy drink-fueled, Dorito-dusted fingers furiously clicking away at keyboards.

"If you are a top gamer - your country needs you," Healey proclaimed, presumably while trying to figure out how to use the 'AIM' button on a PlayStation controller. One can only hope that these digital warriors will be more adept at actual warfare than they are at trash-talking pre-pubescent opponents in Call of Duty lobbies.

Picture, if you will, the future of British military might: A battalion of wheezing, spotty-faced soldiers, armed to the teeth with inhalers and acne cream, led into battle by a squadron of elite gamers who've never seen the sun. It's like a crossover episode between "Revenge of the Nerds" and "Saving Private Ryan," directed by a feverish Terry Gilliam.

But let's not be too hasty in our judgment. After all, this could be a stroke of genius. Who better to navigate the foggy battlefields of tomorrow than those who've spent their lives peering through a haze of Ventolin? And surely, those who've waged war against their own epidermis are well-prepared for the ravages of actual combat.

As for the gamers, well, they've been training for this moment their entire lives. Years of virtual warfare have prepared them for the ultimate boss battle: defending the realm against cyber threats. One can only hope they remember to take bathroom breaks and stay hydrated during their 12-hour shifts at GCHQ.

In this brave new world of military recruitment, one can't help but wonder what's next. Will the Navy start actively seeking out those with chronic seasickness? Perhaps the Air Force will begin courting individuals with a crippling fear of heights?

But fear not, dear citizens. For in this topsy-turvy world where acne is a badge of honor and asthma is a tactical advantage, we can rest easy knowing that our nation's defense is in the capable (if slightly wheezy and pizza-greasy) hands of Britain's finest misfits.

So, to all you basement-dwelling, inhaler-wielding, pimple-popping patriots out there: Your country calls! Grab your gaming mice, strap on your acne pads, and march forth into the glorious, pixelated sunset of Britain's cyber-asthmatic future. Just remember to bring your own hand sanitizer – those game controllers can get rather sticky.

results.satirical_column:
In a stunning display of martial ingenuity, Britain's Defence Secretary John Healey has declared war on common sense, launching a campaign to recruit the wheezing and blemished masses into Her Majesty's Armed Forces. No longer will our nation's acne-riddled youth be relegated to the trenches of their bedrooms, battling only the insurgent forces of social anxiety and disappointing Tinder matches. Now, they can take their struggle to the global stage, armed with nothing but an inhaler and a year's supply of Clearasil.

Picture, if you will, the next great invasion force: battalions of spotty-faced soldiers storming beaches, leaving a trail of shed skin cells in their wake. The enemy, paralyzed with laughter or perhaps pity, will surely surrender at the sight of our glorious troops pausing mid-charge to apply a liberal coating of benzoyl peroxide.

But wait, there's more! In a stroke of genius that would make Sun Tzu weep with envy, Healey has set his sights on the true warriors of our time: gamers. Yes, those brave souls who've honed their skills in the brutal arenas of Call of Duty and Fortnite will now be called upon to serve their country. After all, who better to pilot our drones than someone who's spent countless hours perfecting the art of teabagging virtual corpses?

One can only imagine the rigorous training regimen these new recruits will face. Push-ups replaced by furious button mashing. Obstacle courses swapped for speedruns through Elden Ring. And let's not forget the grueling endurance tests of binge-watching entire seasons of anime without bathroom breaks.

As we usher in this new era of military might, one can't help but wonder what other untapped demographics might bolster our forces. Perhaps we could recruit insomniacs for night watch, their sleepless vigils finally put to good use. Or how about employing chronic procrastinators as strategic advisors? Their ability to rationalize delay could prove invaluable in avoiding unnecessary conflicts.

In the end, we must applaud Healey's visionary approach. For too long, Britain's armed forces have been hampered by such trivial concerns as "physical fitness" and "combat readiness." Now, finally, we can embrace our true national strengths: questionable skin care routines and an unhealthy obsession with pixels.

So stand tall, future defenders of the realm! Your country needs you – spots, wheezes, Cheeto-stained fingers and all. Just remember to pause your game and take a puff of your inhaler before charging into battle. God save the Queen, and may your K/D ratio always be positive.
